1
00:02:54,820 --> 00:02:55,952
<i>CLAIRE: Previously...</i>

2
00:02:55,988 --> 00:02:57,521
<i>Someone tried to poison me.</i>

3
00:02:57,556 --> 00:02:58,789
For you, Madonna.

4
00:02:58,824 --> 00:03:01,910
It will change color in
the presence of poison.

5
00:03:11,126 --> 00:03:12,959
If St. Germain is behind this,

6
00:03:12,995 --> 00:03:14,728
you need to connect him to the gang,

7
00:03:14,763 --> 00:03:15,996
<i>Les Disciples.</i>

8
00:03:16,310 --> 00:03:18,965
- There's nothing in here.
- Look again, Madonna.

9
00:03:19,100 --> 00:03:21,268
- How did you do that?
- A little sleight of hand.

10
00:03:21,303 --> 00:03:24,237
Apostle spoons. Christening
gift for the bairn.

11
00:03:24,273 --> 00:03:27,740
Monsieur Forez confided
to me that he's preparing

12
00:03:27,109 --> 00:03:28,542
for multiple executions.

13
00:03:28,577 --> 00:03:30,243
You're in danger, Master Raymond.

14
00:03:30,279 --> 00:03:31,912
<i>You can't kill Randall.</i>

15
00:03:31,947 --> 00:03:33,513
It would be as if you're
killing Frank too.

16
00:03:33,549 --> 00:03:35,415
A year, not one day more.

17
00:03:35,451 --> 00:03:38,118
Milord got into a fight
with an English officer.

18
00:03:38,153 --> 00:03:40,253
(SPEAKING SOFTLY) He promised.

19
00:03:40,289 --> 00:03:43,957
(BOTH GRUNTING)

20
00:03:43,992 --> 00:03:45,992
Jamie!

21
00:03:47,296 --> 00:03:48,495
Claire!

22
00:03:50,532 --> 00:03:53,166
<i>♪ Sing me a song ♪</i>

23
00:03:53,202 --> 00:03:56,336
<i>♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪</i>

24
00:03:56,371 --> 00:03:59,172
<i>♪ Say, could that lass ♪</i>

25
00:03:59,208 --> 00:04:02,175
<i>♪ Be I? ♪</i>

26
00:04:02,211 --> 00:04:04,100
<i>♪ Merry of soul ♪</i>

27
00:04:04,460 --> 00:04:07,800
<i>♪ She sailed on a day ♪</i>

28
00:04:07,116 --> 00:04:09,149
<i>♪ Over the sea ♪</i>

29
00:03:59,184 --> 00:04:02,319
<i>♪ To Skye ♪</i>

30
00:04:02,354 --> 00:04:04,654
<i>♪ Billow and breeze ♪</i>

31
00:04:04,690 --> 00:04:07,424
<i>♪ Islands and seas ♪</i>

32
00:04:07,459 --> 00:04:12,129
<i>♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪</i>

33
00:04:12,698 --> 00:04:15,165
<i>♪ All that was good ♪</i>

34
00:04:15,200 --> 00:04:18,100
<i>♪ All that was fair ♪</i>

35
00:04:18,360 --> 00:04:20,170
<i>♪ All that was me ♪</i>

36
00:04:20,205 --> 00:04:23,273
<i>♪ Is gone ♪</i>

37
00:04:23,308 --> 00:04:26,276
<i>(SINGING IN FRENCH)</i>

38
00:04:26,311 --> 00:04:29,312
<i>♪</i>

39
00:04:38,690 --> 00:04:42,526
<i>♪ Over the sea ♪</i>

40
00:04:42,561 --> 00:04:47,230
<i>♪ To Skye ♪</i>

41
00:04:48,133 --> 00:04:49,332
<i>♪♪</i>

42
00:04:49,357 --> 00:04:54,120
- sync and corrections by Caio -
- www.addic7ed.com -

43
00:04:57,609 --> 00:05:00,610
<i>♪</i>

44
00:05:12,524 --> 00:05:16,126
Look, Mama. What a pretty bird.

45
00:05:16,161 --> 00:05:18,295
Let me see. (GASPS)

46
00:05:18,330 --> 00:05:20,664
That is a pretty bird, isn't it?

47
00:05:20,699 --> 00:05:22,599
What kind of bird is this?

48
00:05:22,634 --> 00:05:25,702
That is a heron.

49
00:05:25,737 --> 00:05:27,671
Have you ever seen one in real life?

50
00:05:27,706 --> 00:05:29,720
Yes, I have.

51
00:05:29,107 --> 00:05:31,374
- Where?
- In Scotland.

52
00:05:31,410 --> 00:05:33,443
When were you in Scotland, Mama?

53
00:05:33,478 --> 00:05:36,546
(SIGHS)

54
00:05:36,582 --> 00:05:38,215
A long time ago.

55
00:05:38,250 --> 00:05:41,218
(SOFT GAELIC MUSIC)

56
00:05:41,253 --> 00:05:44,254
<i>♪</i>

57
00:06:16,355 --> 00:06:19,489
Claire?

58
00:06:19,524 --> 00:06:23,526
(INDISTINCT MUTTERING)

59
00:06:25,631 --> 00:06:27,364
<i>Be still, my child.</i>

60
00:06:27,399 --> 00:06:30,367
My baby.

61
00:06:30,402 --> 00:06:32,769
I am here.

62
00:06:32,804 --> 00:06:37,741
(INDISTINCT MUTTERING)

63
00:06:37,776 --> 00:06:40,543
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

64
00:06:40,579 --> 00:06:42,779
We will take care of you.

65
00:06:42,814 --> 00:06:44,147
Jamie.

66
00:06:44,182 --> 00:06:45,548
Monsieur Forez is working.

67
00:06:45,584 --> 00:06:46,750
(WHIMPERING)

68
00:06:46,785 --> 00:06:48,184
My baby...

69
00:06:48,220 --> 00:06:51,454
You must stay quiet. You must.

70
00:06:57,529 --> 00:06:59,529
I am here.

71
00:07:09,641 --> 00:07:12,609
(SOFT MUSIC)

72
00:07:12,644 --> 00:07:15,645
<i>♪</i>

73
00:07:36,668 --> 00:07:39,669
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

74
00:07:52,250 --> 00:07:55,185
<i>♪♪</i>

75
00:08:24,683 --> 00:08:27,684
(PANICKED BREATHING)

76
00:08:30,756 --> 00:08:34,190
Where's my baby?

77
00:08:34,226 --> 00:08:37,193
Wh... where is my baby?

78
00:08:37,229 --> 00:08:38,828
<i>Chère</i> Madame,

79
00:08:38,864 --> 00:08:40,430
do not trouble yourself.

80
00:08:40,465 --> 00:08:41,798
You must save your strength.

81
00:08:41,833 --> 00:08:43,833
Where's my baby?

82
00:08:47,939 --> 00:08:49,672
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

83
00:08:49,708 --> 00:08:52,642
I don't want any water. I...

84
00:08:52,677 --> 00:08:55,478
I want my baby.

85
00:08:55,514 --> 00:08:57,414
I am sorry, Madame.

86
00:08:57,449 --> 00:09:00,216
She has joined the angels.

87
00:09:00,252 --> 00:09:03,920
She was...

88
00:09:23,875 --> 00:09:27,477
(WHISPERING) No. No.

89
00:09:29,614 --> 00:09:31,581
It's not possible.

90
00:09:45,864 --> 00:09:48,998
I want my baby.

91
00:09:49,340 --> 00:09:51,670
My... bring me my baby.

92
00:09:51,102 --> 00:09:54,938
(WHIMPERING) Bring me my baby.

93
00:09:54,973 --> 00:09:56,272
Bring me my baby!

94
00:09:56,308 --> 00:09:57,874
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

95
00:09:57,909 --> 00:10:02,450
I want my baby! Baby!

96
00:10:02,800 --> 00:10:03,847
(STATUE SHATTERING)

97
00:10:17,929 --> 00:10:20,597
Shh.

98
00:10:20,632 --> 00:10:22,999
Shh.

99
00:10:23,340 --> 00:10:24,801
(SPEAKING SOFTLY) Where is she now?

100
00:10:24,836 --> 00:10:26,703
I baptized her.

101
00:10:26,738 --> 00:10:29,405
And gave her a name.

102
00:10:29,441 --> 00:10:32,800
Faith.

103
00:10:32,430 --> 00:10:33,743
You must understand,

104
00:10:33,778 --> 00:10:36,913
it is illegal unless
the child is living.

105
00:10:36,948 --> 00:10:41,918
But I wanted her to be
buried in hallowed ground.

106
00:10:41,953 --> 00:10:43,586
This,<i> ma chère,</i>

107
00:10:43,622 --> 00:10:47,857
will stay between you, me, and God.

108
00:10:47,893 --> 00:10:50,960
(RASPY BREATHING)

109
00:10:52,931 --> 00:10:55,131
<i>Mère</i> Hildegarde...

110
00:10:59,700 --> 00:11:01,738
This is Father Laurentin.

111
00:11:01,773 --> 00:11:03,706
It is customary to perform

112
00:11:03,742 --> 00:11:06,543
an unction of the sick, my child.

113
00:11:06,578 --> 00:11:09,379
It has been several days now.

114
00:11:09,414 --> 00:11:11,514
Your fever is very high.

115
00:11:11,550 --> 00:11:14,551
It is wise to prepare the soul.

116
00:11:16,688 --> 00:11:19,455
I need my husband.

117
00:11:19,491 --> 00:11:22,792
I'm sorry,<i> ma chère,</i>
there has been no word.

118
00:11:33,638 --> 00:11:37,407
My sins are all I have left.

119
00:11:37,442 --> 00:11:40,410
(SOFT MUSIC)

120
00:11:40,445 --> 00:11:43,446
<i>♪</i>

121
00:11:52,190 --> 00:11:55,191
(SPEAKING LATIN)

122
00:11:57,762 --> 00:12:00,897
- Amen.
- Amen.

123
00:12:00,932 --> 00:12:03,933
Bouton...

124
00:12:05,937 --> 00:12:08,938
(RASPY BREATHING)

125
00:12:18,850 --> 00:12:21,851
(WHIMPERING)

126
00:12:30,161 --> 00:12:31,794
(DOG GROWLING)

127
00:12:35,900 --> 00:12:38,568
(WHIMPERING)

128
00:12:38,603 --> 00:12:40,536
(SPEAKING SOFTLY) Be still now.

129
00:12:40,572 --> 00:12:42,380
- Jamie...
- Shh, shh, shh.

130
00:12:42,730 --> 00:12:43,573
Hush, Madonna.

131
00:12:43,608 --> 00:12:46,275
If they find me here, I'm finished.

132
00:12:48,647 --> 00:12:50,580
Master Raymond.

133
00:12:50,615 --> 00:12:52,682
Tell me what you see, Madonna.

134
00:12:58,556 --> 00:13:01,524
CLAIRE: Oh, wings.

135
00:13:09,340 --> 00:13:11,567
Blue wings.

136
00:13:11,603 --> 00:13:15,571
Mm, blue with the color of healing.

137
00:13:15,607 --> 00:13:19,575
The wings will carry your
pain away, if you let them.

138
00:13:19,611 --> 00:13:23,212
<i>CLAIRE: A white hotness
burned deep in my bones.</i>

139
00:13:23,248 --> 00:13:25,148
<i>I knew what it was.</i>

140
00:13:25,183 --> 00:13:27,283
<i>Puerperal fever.</i>

141
00:13:27,318 --> 00:13:29,185
<i>The baby had come,</i>

142
00:13:29,220 --> 00:13:31,988
<i>but part of the placenta had not.</i>

143
00:13:32,230 --> 00:13:34,857
<i>It festered inside my womb,</i>

144
00:13:34,893 --> 00:13:39,262
<i>but as Raymond's hands moved
over the meridians of my body,</i>

145
00:13:39,297 --> 00:13:42,980
<i>I could feel the tiny
deaths of the bacteria</i>

146
00:13:42,133 --> 00:13:45,234
<i>that inhabited my
blood, small explosions</i>

147
00:13:45,270 --> 00:13:48,671
<i>as each scintilla of
infection disappeared.</i>

148
00:13:48,707 --> 00:13:51,740
<i>The fever drained from my bones,</i>

149
00:13:51,109 --> 00:13:53,342
<i>and my tortured body relaxed gratefully</i>

150
00:13:53,378 --> 00:13:55,745
<i>into the frame of his hands,</i>

151
00:13:55,780 --> 00:13:59,282
<i>melting and reforming like molded wax.</i>

152
00:14:03,154 --> 00:14:05,888
(GROANS)

153
00:14:05,924 --> 00:14:08,958
(INHALES DEEPLY)

154
00:14:08,993 --> 00:14:11,828
Call him.

155
00:14:11,863 --> 00:14:15,898
(GROANS)

156
00:14:15,934 --> 00:14:19,202
- Call to him.
- (GRUNTING)

157
00:14:19,237 --> 00:14:22,905
Jamie!

158
00:14:22,941 --> 00:14:26,175
(GRUNTING)

159
00:14:26,211 --> 00:14:27,777
<i>CLAIRE: I don't know what he did</i>

160
00:14:27,812 --> 00:14:29,212
<i>or how he did it...</i>

161
00:14:29,247 --> 00:14:30,980
(DOOR OPENS)

162
00:14:31,150 --> 00:14:32,215
<i>But he healed me.</i>

163
00:14:32,250 --> 00:14:33,883
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

164
00:14:33,918 --> 00:14:38,221
<i>Once more, he saved my life.</i>

165
00:14:38,256 --> 00:14:39,989
Madame?

166
00:14:59,944 --> 00:15:03,112
I must go now. Be well, Madonna.

167
00:15:03,148 --> 00:15:05,648
I am no Madonna.

168
00:15:05,683 --> 00:15:07,383
I have no child.

169
00:15:07,418 --> 00:15:08,818
I didn't call you Madonna

170
00:15:08,853 --> 00:15:11,988
because you were with child, my dear.

171
00:15:12,230 --> 00:15:14,390
Everyone has a color about them,

172
00:15:14,425 --> 00:15:17,794
all around them like a cloud.

173
00:15:17,829 --> 00:15:19,162
Yours is blue.

174
00:15:19,197 --> 00:15:21,300
Like the Virgin's cloak.

175
00:15:21,650 --> 00:15:24,330
Like my own.

176
00:15:24,680 --> 00:15:26,269
You shouldn't have come.

177
00:15:26,304 --> 00:15:28,370
It's too dangerous.

178
00:15:28,720 --> 00:15:29,405
You were right about the king.

179
00:15:29,440 --> 00:15:31,274
He wants blood now.

180
00:15:33,452 --> 00:15:38,880
But these are things you
do for your friends.

181
00:15:38,116 --> 00:15:40,950
Will I ever see you again?

182
00:15:40,985 --> 00:15:44,987
As I told you before, we
will see each other again.

183
00:15:48,259 --> 00:15:52,795
(DOOR OPENING, FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

184
00:16:03,875 --> 00:16:05,174
(GASPS)

185
00:16:20,910 --> 00:16:24,727
Mère, has there been any
word from Monsieur Fraser?

186
00:16:24,762 --> 00:16:27,196
He is unable to come, Madame.

187
00:16:27,232 --> 00:16:31,670
He was arrested for dueling
with the English captain,

188
00:16:31,102 --> 00:16:35,938
and is being detained in the
Bastille Saint-Antoine.

189
00:16:35,974 --> 00:16:37,874
For how long?

190
00:16:37,909 --> 00:16:40,476
Dueling is a serious offense.

191
00:16:40,511 --> 00:16:43,813
I'm afraid your husband
will remain in prison

192
00:16:43,848 --> 00:16:46,349
at the king's pleasure.

193
00:16:46,384 --> 00:16:49,385
If your husband had killed his opponent,

194
00:16:49,420 --> 00:16:52,822
the penalty would have been much worse.

195
00:16:52,857 --> 00:16:54,824
He's not dead?

196
00:16:54,859 --> 00:16:57,526
The English captain?

197
00:16:57,562 --> 00:16:59,395
He is badly wounded,

198
00:16:59,430 --> 00:17:02,431
and the British ambassador
begged for him to be allowed

199
00:17:02,467 --> 00:17:06,402
to recover from his injuries in England.

200
00:17:06,437 --> 00:17:09,338
<i>CLAIRE: So Jack Randall was still alive.</i>

201
00:17:09,374 --> 00:17:12,308
<i>The cat with nine lives.</i>

202
00:17:12,343 --> 00:17:16,379
<i>And thus, so was Frank.</i>

203
00:17:16,414 --> 00:17:17,980
<i>But at what cost?</i>

204
00:17:18,160 --> 00:17:21,350
That is fortunate, no?

205
00:17:21,386 --> 00:17:22,551
Yes.

206
00:17:25,290 --> 00:17:28,900
Fortunate.

207
00:17:28,126 --> 00:17:30,993
But my husband betrayed me, Mother.

208
00:17:31,290 --> 00:17:34,830
Revenge mattered more to him than me...

209
00:17:36,301 --> 00:17:38,868
or his child.

210
00:17:38,903 --> 00:17:42,405
How so?

211
00:17:42,440 --> 00:17:46,208
One year of grace

212
00:17:46,244 --> 00:17:50,460
is all I asked,

213
00:17:50,810 --> 00:17:54,183
to which he agreed.

214
00:17:54,218 --> 00:17:56,385
One year.

215
00:17:56,421 --> 00:18:01,157
He may as well have run
his sword through me.

216
00:18:04,562 --> 00:18:08,297
God says we must revel in mercy.

217
00:18:08,333 --> 00:18:11,500
Tread sins underfoot

218
00:18:11,536 --> 00:18:16,405
and hurl iniquities into the sea.

219
00:18:16,441 --> 00:18:20,843
I'm not sure there's a sea deep enough.

220
00:18:20,878 --> 00:18:23,813
(SOFT MUSIC)

221
00:18:23,848 --> 00:18:26,849
<i>♪</i>

222
00:18:34,959 --> 00:18:37,560
<i>CLAIRE: I laid in that bed for weeks.</i>

223
00:18:37,595 --> 00:18:42,298
<i>My body had healed. My soul had not.</i>

224
00:18:42,333 --> 00:18:45,267
<i>One day Fergus came.</i>

225
00:18:45,303 --> 00:18:50,239
<i>He brought flowers and
asked me to come home.</i>

226
00:18:50,274 --> 00:18:54,643
<i>I'd lost my husband and my child.</i>

227
00:18:54,679 --> 00:18:57,546
<i>Where else could I go?</i>

228
00:18:57,582 --> 00:19:00,583
<i>♪</i>

229
00:19:00,618 --> 00:19:03,586
(SOMBER MUSIC)

230
00:19:03,621 --> 00:19:06,622
<i>♪</i>

231
00:20:12,323 --> 00:20:15,324
(SOBBING)

232
00:20:22,767 --> 00:20:25,468
Welcome home...

233
00:20:25,503 --> 00:20:27,369
Milady.

234
00:20:27,405 --> 00:20:30,406
<i>♪</i>

235
00:20:44,722 --> 00:20:47,656
Thank you, Magnus.

236
00:20:47,692 --> 00:20:50,726
(SOMBER MUSIC)

237
00:20:50,761 --> 00:20:53,762
<i>♪</i>

238
00:21:33,738 --> 00:21:35,471
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

239
00:21:40,444 --> 00:21:42,578
Thank you, Fergus.

240
00:21:42,613 --> 00:21:44,246
That was nice.

241
00:21:55,793 --> 00:21:58,694
(OMINOUS MUSIC)

242
00:21:58,729 --> 00:22:01,730
<i>♪</i>

243
00:22:06,837 --> 00:22:08,470
What is it?

244
00:22:08,506 --> 00:22:11,473
N... nothing, Milady.

245
00:22:14,245 --> 00:22:15,911
(DOOR CLOSING)

246
00:22:49,947 --> 00:22:52,881
(SOMBER MUSIC)

247
00:22:52,917 --> 00:22:55,918
<i>♪</i>

248
00:23:00,858 --> 00:23:03,325
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

249
00:23:03,361 --> 00:23:04,560
(GRUNTS)

250
00:23:10,835 --> 00:23:13,836
(FAINT WHIMPERING)

251
00:23:33,257 --> 00:23:35,691
<i>FERGUS: No!</i>

252
00:23:35,726 --> 00:23:39,495
<i>What is he doing?</i>

253
00:23:39,530 --> 00:23:41,297
Stop!

254
00:23:41,332 --> 00:23:44,733
(WHIMPERING)

255
00:23:44,769 --> 00:23:47,903
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

256
00:23:47,938 --> 00:23:51,473
Fergus?

257
00:23:51,509 --> 00:23:52,741
Wake up.

258
00:23:52,777 --> 00:23:55,778
It's just a bad dream.

259
00:23:58,482 --> 00:24:01,517
Do you want to tell me about it?

260
00:24:01,552 --> 00:24:05,587
No. No, Milady.

261
00:24:05,623 --> 00:24:09,425
Might make you feel better.

262
00:24:09,460 --> 00:24:13,329
It's... it... it's not just a dream.

263
00:24:15,800 --> 00:24:18,467
What is it?

264
00:24:18,502 --> 00:24:20,936
The... the Englishman, Milady.

265
00:24:25,609 --> 00:24:27,609
What Englishman?

266
00:24:29,714 --> 00:24:31,680
Fergus, tell me.

267
00:24:35,319 --> 00:24:39,355
I-I went with Milord to...
to Maison Elise.

268
00:24:39,390 --> 00:24:41,323
<i>Prince Charles owed money.</i>

269
00:24:41,359 --> 00:24:42,391
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

270
00:24:42,426 --> 00:24:43,992
<i>FERGUS: He told me to wait.</i>

271
00:24:44,280 --> 00:24:45,961
<i>Milord told me to stay put,</i>

272
00:24:45,996 --> 00:24:48,564
<i>but I have a talent for stealing</i>

273
00:24:48,599 --> 00:24:50,532
<i>and I couldn't resist.</i>

274
00:24:50,568 --> 00:24:54,837
O... one of the rooms was open...

275
00:24:54,872 --> 00:24:58,307
<i>and I saw a bottle of perfume there.</i>

276
00:24:58,342 --> 00:25:01,744
<i>I-I-I wanted to bring
it to Milady as a gift.</i>

277
00:25:01,779 --> 00:25:03,579
<i>It smelled so nice.</i>

278
00:25:03,614 --> 00:25:05,414
<i>I put it in my pocket.</i>

279
00:25:05,449 --> 00:25:09,451
I kept the bottle, but...

280
00:25:09,487 --> 00:25:11,120
but I was too afraid to give it to you

281
00:25:11,155 --> 00:25:12,554
after what happened.

282
00:25:22,166 --> 00:25:24,466
It's lavender, Milady.

283
00:25:27,405 --> 00:25:29,805
When I turned around,

284
00:25:29,840 --> 00:25:32,875
<i>he was there. The Englishman.</i>

285
00:25:32,910 --> 00:25:37,546
You're not what I ordered.

286
00:25:37,581 --> 00:25:40,949
But, um...

287
00:25:40,985 --> 00:25:42,551
no, you'll do.

288
00:25:42,586 --> 00:25:44,987
(WHISPERING) Jesus Christ.

289
00:25:45,220 --> 00:25:47,623
I-I tried to get away, I swear I did.

290
00:25:47,658 --> 00:25:49,458
I told him Milord was there,

291
00:25:49,493 --> 00:25:52,995
but he... he wouldn't listen.

292
00:25:53,300 --> 00:25:56,632
He said that h-h-h-he wanted me to...

293
00:26:01,972 --> 00:26:06,875
I can't say it in front of a lady.

294
00:26:06,911 --> 00:26:10,646
(GRUNTS) Stop! Stop!

295
00:26:10,681 --> 00:26:13,810
Why... why didn't you
tell me this sooner?

296
00:26:13,117 --> 00:26:16,118
I-I wanted to, but...

297
00:26:18,155 --> 00:26:19,922
but I was ashamed.

298
00:26:19,957 --> 00:26:21,590
It's all right, Fergus.

299
00:26:21,625 --> 00:26:25,160
No! No, it's not.

300
00:26:25,196 --> 00:26:27,563
It's all my fault.

301
00:26:27,598 --> 00:26:30,799
I should have kept quiet.

302
00:26:30,835 --> 00:26:32,801
I didn't cry or scream at first,

303
00:26:32,837 --> 00:26:37,473
but... I couldn't help it.

304
00:26:37,508 --> 00:26:40,209
Stop! Stop! Stop!

305
00:26:40,244 --> 00:26:42,878
<i>Milord!</i>

306
00:26:42,913 --> 00:26:46,181
Milord heard it and...

307
00:26:46,217 --> 00:26:47,783
and he came running.

308
00:26:47,818 --> 00:26:49,885
Milord!

309
00:26:52,256 --> 00:26:55,257
(BOTH GRUNTING)

310
00:26:57,962 --> 00:26:59,628
<i>I hid under the dressing table.</i>

311
00:26:59,663 --> 00:27:03,131
- (GRUNTING)
- Get off!

312
00:27:03,167 --> 00:27:05,934
<i>Then the fight was broken up.</i>

313
00:27:05,970 --> 00:27:09,538
A-as soon as Milord was taken away,

314
00:27:09,573 --> 00:27:12,808
I heard him challenge the
Englishman to a duel.

315
00:27:12,843 --> 00:27:15,644
You sick bastard!

316
00:27:15,679 --> 00:27:18,814
A duel! I demand a duel!

317
00:27:18,849 --> 00:27:20,949
No! (GRUNTS)

318
00:27:20,985 --> 00:27:23,285
<i>And then he was taken away.</i>

319
00:27:26,857 --> 00:27:28,857
(GROANS)

320
00:27:28,893 --> 00:27:31,260
It's not your fault, Fergus.

321
00:27:31,295 --> 00:27:32,995
I-I didn't know.

322
00:27:33,300 --> 00:27:36,532
I didn't know he would go
to fight the Englishman.

323
00:27:36,567 --> 00:27:38,534
I didn't know.

324
00:27:38,569 --> 00:27:40,969
A... and now Milord is gone.

325
00:27:41,500 --> 00:27:45,173
He will never come back.

326
00:27:45,209 --> 00:27:46,642
Come here.

327
00:27:46,677 --> 00:27:48,277
Oh, it's all right.

328
00:27:54,885 --> 00:27:59,154
A private audience with the king?

329
00:27:59,189 --> 00:28:01,223
You have mentioned you
are the goddaughter

330
00:28:01,258 --> 00:28:02,891
of the Old Sun King.

331
00:28:02,927 --> 00:28:06,995
Surely you have an entrée
or know someone who does.

332
00:28:09,700 --> 00:28:14,202
It is possible.

333
00:28:14,238 --> 00:28:16,672
I wish to petition for
my husband's release

334
00:28:16,707 --> 00:28:18,840
from the Bastille.

335
00:28:18,876 --> 00:28:23,211
So, ma chère, you have
found a deep enough sea.

336
00:28:26,150 --> 00:28:29,952
I learned the reason
he broke his promise.

337
00:28:29,987 --> 00:28:32,521
I was angry at him.

338
00:28:32,556 --> 00:28:34,957
Still am.

339
00:28:34,992 --> 00:28:37,960
But he is the father of my child.

340
00:28:41,298 --> 00:28:46,268
His Majesty is a mercurial man.

341
00:28:46,303 --> 00:28:50,772
There is a price to such requests.

342
00:28:50,808 --> 00:28:52,774
Which is?

343
00:28:52,810 --> 00:28:56,440
The king may expect to lie with you.

344
00:29:02,953 --> 00:29:07,923
If it comes to sacrificing
my virtue, Mother,

345
00:29:07,958 --> 00:29:09,958
I'll add it to the list of things

346
00:29:09,994 --> 00:29:12,600
I have already lost in Paris.

347
00:29:29,713 --> 00:29:32,648
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

348
00:29:32,683 --> 00:29:35,684
<i>♪</i>

349
00:30:00,778 --> 00:30:03,645
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

350
00:30:03,681 --> 00:30:06,815
(SPEAKING FRENCH)

351
00:30:06,850 --> 00:30:10,786
Madame Claire Fraser,
Lady Broch Tuarach.

352
00:30:30,407 --> 00:30:31,940
No.

353
00:31:27,831 --> 00:31:29,431
(SNIFFING)

354
00:31:32,202 --> 00:31:33,368
Mmm.

355
00:31:42,640 --> 00:31:46,410
Now, tell me what it is
that I may do for you.

356
00:31:48,680 --> 00:31:52,816
My husband is in the Bastille.

357
00:31:52,841 --> 00:31:54,908
For dueling.

358
00:31:54,933 --> 00:31:59,669
Your husband has broken a royal decree.

359
00:31:59,897 --> 00:32:02,531
I understand that.

360
00:32:02,566 --> 00:32:06,968
But he was provoked.

361
00:32:07,400 --> 00:32:09,838
As you know, he is a Scot.

362
00:32:09,873 --> 00:32:11,907
They are most fierce where questions

363
00:32:11,942 --> 00:32:14,109
of their honor are concerned.

364
00:32:14,144 --> 00:32:16,411
Quite so.

365
00:32:16,446 --> 00:32:20,182
Quite so, Madame.

366
00:32:20,217 --> 00:32:24,920
- However...
- I would be most grateful...

367
00:32:24,955 --> 00:32:26,588
Your Majesty.

368
00:32:35,632 --> 00:32:38,466
Is this his ring?

369
00:32:38,502 --> 00:32:40,502
Yes, Sire.

370
00:32:44,107 --> 00:32:47,108
And this other one?

371
00:32:49,913 --> 00:32:53,480
I was married once before.

372
00:32:55,180 --> 00:32:58,453
And yet you still wear his ring.

373
00:32:58,488 --> 00:33:01,489
Your loyalty is most...

374
00:33:01,525 --> 00:33:03,525
noteworthy.

375
00:33:26,550 --> 00:33:30,385
I am inclined towards mercy,

376
00:33:30,420 --> 00:33:32,320
<i>ma chère Madame,</i>

377
00:33:32,356 --> 00:33:35,557
but...

378
00:33:35,592 --> 00:33:38,627
<i>CLAIRE: He was called
Louis the Well-Beloved.</i>

379
00:33:38,662 --> 00:33:41,229
<i>His rule was absolute.</i>

380
00:33:41,265 --> 00:33:43,231
<i>He could free Jamie with a word</i>

381
00:33:43,267 --> 00:33:45,166
<i>or kill him.</i>

382
00:33:45,202 --> 00:33:47,469
<i>He could do with me as he liked.</i>

383
00:33:47,504 --> 00:33:50,772
<i>I waited to see what His
Majesty's pleasure might be.</i>

384
00:33:50,807 --> 00:33:54,309
Tell me, if I was to grant your request

385
00:33:54,344 --> 00:33:57,679
to free your husband...

386
00:33:57,714 --> 00:34:01,983
would you be inclined to grant
me a small favor in return?

387
00:34:04,521 --> 00:34:09,524
I am at Your Majesty's
complete disposal.

388
00:34:10,560 --> 00:34:15,230
Ah. <i>Très bien.</i>

389
00:34:15,265 --> 00:34:19,334
<i>Très bien, ma chère.</i>

390
00:34:19,369 --> 00:34:21,469
Come.

391
00:34:46,296 --> 00:34:49,431
So pale.

392
00:34:49,466 --> 00:34:53,234
So fine.

393
00:34:53,270 --> 00:34:57,672
I can see why they call
you <i>La Dame Blanche.</i>

394
00:34:57,708 --> 00:35:00,709
(SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC)

395
00:35:00,744 --> 00:35:03,712
<i>♪</i>

396
00:35:53,397 --> 00:35:57,399
The king asks that you give us
the benefit of your skills.

397
00:35:57,434 --> 00:35:59,167
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

398
00:36:02,270 --> 00:36:04,300
<i>CLAIRE: When I saw Monsieur Forez,</i>

399
00:36:04,280 --> 00:36:05,928
<i>the king's executioner,</i>

400
00:36:06,118 --> 00:36:09,353
<i>I knew his presence could
mean only one thing:</i>

401
00:36:09,388 --> 00:36:12,256
<i>there would be death here today.</i>

402
00:36:12,291 --> 00:36:15,426
I'm not sure what you mean, Sire.

403
00:36:37,216 --> 00:36:41,518
Maître Raymond et Comte St. Germain,

404
00:37:07,130 --> 00:37:11,548
We have no quarrel with the
proper search for wisdom.

405
00:37:11,584 --> 00:37:14,618
But while much good may be found,

406
00:37:14,654 --> 00:37:17,554
so, too, may evil be discovered.

407
00:37:17,590 --> 00:37:21,659
And the search for
wisdom be perverted into

408
00:37:21,694 --> 00:37:23,928
the desire for power and wealth

409
00:37:23,963 --> 00:37:27,197
for one's own depraved
and immoral purpose.

410
00:37:56,128 --> 00:37:58,329
(WHISPERING) Jesus H. Roosevelt Christ.

411
00:37:58,364 --> 00:38:00,497
I beseech you to use your talents,

412
00:38:00,533 --> 00:38:02,700
look into their souls

413
00:38:02,735 --> 00:38:05,569
and if there is darkness within,

414
00:38:05,604 --> 00:38:08,172
they will be handed
over to M'sieur Forez

415
00:38:08,207 --> 00:38:09,707
and put to death.

416
00:38:09,742 --> 00:38:12,710
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

417
00:38:12,745 --> 00:38:15,746
<i>♪</i>

418
00:38:18,117 --> 00:38:20,684
It will be an honor

419
00:38:20,720 --> 00:38:23,654
to assist Your Majesty in this task.

420
00:38:23,689 --> 00:38:26,230
Very well.

421
00:38:26,580 --> 00:38:27,624
Let us commence.

422
00:39:00,326 --> 00:39:03,260
I see a shadow...

423
00:39:03,295 --> 00:39:07,431
behind your eyes, Comte.

424
00:39:07,466 --> 00:39:09,433
(NERVOUS CHUCKLE)

425
00:39:16,409 --> 00:39:18,442
(NERVOUS CHUCKLE)

426
00:39:23,449 --> 00:39:26,683
I see an image.

427
00:39:26,719 --> 00:39:30,320
A gang of men in the street...

428
00:39:30,356 --> 00:39:32,156
dressed as aristocrats,

429
00:39:32,191 --> 00:39:34,625
but wearing masks.

430
00:39:36,695 --> 00:39:39,396
There is a name in
your mind, Monsieur...

431
00:39:43,536 --> 00:39:45,803
- "Les Disciples."
- (SCOFFS)

432
00:39:50,709 --> 00:39:53,343
What do you know of "Les
Disciples," Monsieur?

433
00:39:53,379 --> 00:39:56,814
I know nothing of these
"Disciples" of which you speak.

434
00:39:56,849 --> 00:39:59,917
- You are lying, sir.
- I am not lying.

435
00:39:59,952 --> 00:40:04,721
I am not lying! I am not lying, Sire!

436
00:40:04,757 --> 00:40:08,225
This woman is a liar and a witch.

437
00:40:08,260 --> 00:40:11,395
This woman has also been known
to drink poison and survive.

438
00:40:11,430 --> 00:40:13,230
And how do you come to this knowledge?

439
00:40:13,265 --> 00:40:16,667
Because I gave her the poison myself.

440
00:40:23,375 --> 00:40:26,510
She tried to ruin my livelihood.

441
00:40:26,545 --> 00:40:30,214
She had my ship destroyed
with her false condemnations.

442
00:40:30,249 --> 00:40:33,484
She is a witch.

443
00:40:33,519 --> 00:40:35,552
And she doesn't deny it.

444
00:40:38,591 --> 00:40:40,224
(SCOFFS)

445
00:40:40,259 --> 00:40:42,960
No.

446
00:40:42,995 --> 00:40:47,498
I don't deny it.

447
00:40:47,533 --> 00:40:52,469
<i>La Dame Blanche</i> is a white witch,

448
00:40:52,505 --> 00:40:54,838
and I practice...

449
00:40:54,874 --> 00:40:58,709
white magic, Sire.

450
00:41:00,980 --> 00:41:04,581
Madame Fraser

451
00:41:04,617 --> 00:41:07,417
is not on trial here.

452
00:41:09,955 --> 00:41:13,557
<i>CLAIRE: Even knowing St.
Germain tried to poison me,</i>

453
00:41:13,592 --> 00:41:18,362
<i>I found it hard to condemn
him cold-bloodedly to death.</i>

454
00:41:18,397 --> 00:41:20,631
(SPEAKING SOFTLY) I see
darkness in his soul.

455
00:41:28,914 --> 00:41:32,415
Also in his.

456
00:41:32,912 --> 00:41:34,912
But only the normal darkness

457
00:41:34,947 --> 00:41:38,582
that lives in the souls of...

458
00:41:38,617 --> 00:41:40,617
all men.

459
00:41:48,360 --> 00:41:49,993
Even a king's.

460
00:41:57,503 --> 00:42:01,371
For without darkness...

461
00:42:01,407 --> 00:42:03,473
there can be no light.

462
00:42:06,412 --> 00:42:09,713
Nevertheless, if I am
to cleanse this city,

463
00:42:09,748 --> 00:42:11,810
I must make an example.

464
00:42:11,116 --> 00:42:12,282
(SCOFFS)

465
00:42:14,887 --> 00:42:19,356
Perhaps we can aid your decision.

466
00:42:21,327 --> 00:42:24,328
(RUMBLING)

467
00:42:29,335 --> 00:42:32,302
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

468
00:42:32,338 --> 00:42:35,339
<i>♪</i>

469
00:42:38,510 --> 00:42:41,345
The Bible claims that a true believer

470
00:42:41,380 --> 00:42:45,415
can handle serpents and
they will not harm him,

471
00:42:45,451 --> 00:42:48,619
for they are the servants of God.

472
00:42:55,828 --> 00:42:59,960
Perhaps, Your Majesty,

473
00:42:59,131 --> 00:43:01,980
I may suggest another test.

474
00:43:08,641 --> 00:43:11,475
It is true I drank the Comte's poison

475
00:43:11,510 --> 00:43:13,510
and it did not kill me.

476
00:43:13,545 --> 00:43:17,481
Let him drink mine and see what happens.

477
00:43:17,516 --> 00:43:19,950
Let them both drink it.

478
00:43:19,985 --> 00:43:21,451
With your permission?

479
00:43:28,661 --> 00:43:29,860
Very well.

480
00:43:31,764 --> 00:43:33,497
<i>CLAIRE: I decided to take a page</i>

481
00:43:33,532 --> 00:43:36,330
<i>out of Master Raymond's
book, so to speak.</i>

482
00:43:36,680 --> 00:43:39,503
<i>I looked through the evidence,
the remnants from his shop</i>

483
00:43:39,538 --> 00:43:41,838
<i>and found the herb I was looking for.</i>

484
00:43:41,874 --> 00:43:44,675
<i>Bitter cascara.</i>

485
00:43:44,710 --> 00:43:47,440
<i>I knew the cascara would
make both men ill,</i>

486
00:43:47,790 --> 00:43:49,120
<i>but wouldn't kill them.</i>

487
00:43:49,480 --> 00:43:51,481
<i>And perhaps Louis, having had his show,</i>

488
00:43:51,517 --> 00:43:54,718
<i>would be appeased and set them free.</i>

489
00:43:58,900 --> 00:44:01,725
This potion will give
you your answers, Sire.

490
00:44:05,597 --> 00:44:08,932
We may have a death...

491
00:44:08,967 --> 00:44:10,967
or two.

492
00:44:13,172 --> 00:44:15,605
But I ask one thing:

493
00:44:15,641 --> 00:44:17,974
if both these men survive,

494
00:44:18,100 --> 00:44:20,770
you will set them free.

495
00:44:23,649 --> 00:44:27,751
We shall see if it pleases the king.

496
00:44:31,790 --> 00:44:34,758
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

497
00:44:34,793 --> 00:44:37,794
<i>♪</i>

498
00:45:05,524 --> 00:45:09,793
(CHOKES)

499
00:45:09,828 --> 00:45:12,662
(GAGS)

500
00:45:12,698 --> 00:45:14,640
(COUGHS)

501
00:45:14,990 --> 00:45:17,100
(GRUNTING)

502
00:45:23,275 --> 00:45:26,276
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

503
00:45:32,351 --> 00:45:35,318
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

504
00:45:35,354 --> 00:45:38,321
<i>♪</i>

505
00:45:53,305 --> 00:45:57,741
<i>CLAIRE: I never saw Raymond add
anything to it, no one had.</i>

506
00:45:57,776 --> 00:46:00,877
<i>It was another amazing
feat, a sleight of hand</i>

507
00:46:00,913 --> 00:46:03,130
<i>like the one he'd shown me in his shop.</i>

508
00:46:13,325 --> 00:46:17,930
Give him the cup.

509
00:46:17,129 --> 00:46:18,328
Hand it to him.

510
00:46:24,403 --> 00:46:26,903
<i>CLAIRE: All I knew was that this time,</i>

511
00:46:26,939 --> 00:46:31,708
<i>inside the cup, was death.</i>

512
00:46:31,743 --> 00:46:33,710
<i>St. Germain knew it too.</i>

513
00:46:33,745 --> 00:46:35,745
(NERVOUS CHUCKLE)

514
00:46:39,718 --> 00:46:42,385
Oh, well...

515
00:47:19,324 --> 00:47:22,292
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

516
00:47:22,327 --> 00:47:25,328
<i>♪</i>

517
00:47:35,274 --> 00:47:37,908
(CUP CLATTERING)

518
00:47:37,943 --> 00:47:40,944
<i>♪</i>

519
00:47:50,455 --> 00:47:53,456
(GRUNTING)

520
00:48:06,710 --> 00:48:09,720
(GROANING)

521
00:48:15,800 --> 00:48:16,790
(SIGHING)

522
00:48:43,976 --> 00:48:45,275
<i>CLAIRE: Perhaps it was the shock</i>

523
00:48:45,310 --> 00:48:46,977
<i>of what I'd been through,</i>

524
00:48:47,120 --> 00:48:49,479
<i>but as Master Raymond was led away,</i>

525
00:48:49,514 --> 00:48:52,582
<i>what ran through my brain
was a line from a film.</i>

526
00:48:52,618 --> 00:48:54,384
<i>You know the one:</i>

527
00:48:54,419 --> 00:48:57,887
<i>"I'm going to miss you most of all."</i>

528
00:48:57,923 --> 00:48:59,456
(DOOR CLOSING)

529
00:49:12,537 --> 00:49:17,140
Your Majesty will honor my request?

530
00:49:17,175 --> 00:49:20,877
First, there's still a
matter of the payment.

531
00:49:42,267 --> 00:49:44,670
(GASPING)

532
00:49:53,512 --> 00:49:55,101
<i>CLAIRE: I closed my eyes</i>

533
00:49:55,126 --> 00:49:57,304
(CLASSICAL MUSIC)

534
00:49:57,329 --> 00:49:59,484
<i>and thought of England.</i>

535
00:50:00,352 --> 00:50:03,353
<i>♪</i>

536
00:50:20,105 --> 00:50:21,304
<i>♪♪</i>

537
00:50:43,950 --> 00:50:45,195
I will issue a pardon for your husband

538
00:50:45,230 --> 00:50:47,130
and arrange one with the English crown

539
00:50:47,165 --> 00:50:50,100
should you wish to return to Scotland.

540
00:51:06,151 --> 00:51:09,119
(DRAMATIC MUSIC)

541
00:51:09,154 --> 00:51:12,122
<i>♪</i>

542
00:51:34,646 --> 00:51:36,179
(CLEARS THROAT)

543
00:52:44,449 --> 00:52:47,817
(CLOCK TICKING)

544
00:52:47,853 --> 00:52:52,355
I don't even know if it was a boy...

545
00:52:52,390 --> 00:52:54,390
or a girl.

546
00:52:59,531 --> 00:53:01,531
(WHISPERING) Claire?

547
00:53:04,536 --> 00:53:06,536
Will ye make me beg?

548
00:53:38,536 --> 00:53:41,905
It was a girl.

549
00:53:41,940 --> 00:53:45,808
Mother Hildegarde baptized her.

550
00:53:45,844 --> 00:53:49,512
Gave her a name.

551
00:53:49,547 --> 00:53:51,547
Faith.

552
00:53:53,551 --> 00:53:57,520
Mother Hildegarde has a
very odd sense of humor.

553
00:54:00,625 --> 00:54:02,792
She's buried in the cemetery,

554
00:54:02,827 --> 00:54:05,728
next to the convent.

555
00:54:07,933 --> 00:54:10,433
I did try to keep my promise.

556
00:54:15,307 --> 00:54:17,507
Fergus told me what happened.

557
00:54:17,542 --> 00:54:20,877
Then ye see how I couldna
let Randall go unpunished

558
00:54:20,912 --> 00:54:23,246
for what he did to the wee lad?

559
00:54:33,525 --> 00:54:35,758
Do ye hate me for it, Claire?

560
00:54:44,269 --> 00:54:46,269
(SPEAKING SOFTLY) I did hate you.

561
00:54:46,304 --> 00:54:49,305
(CLOCK TICKING)

562
00:54:52,477 --> 00:54:55,878
(INAUDIBLE)

563
00:54:55,914 --> 00:55:00,483
(CLOCK CONTINUES TICKING)

564
00:55:00,518 --> 00:55:04,721
Mother Hildegarde let me see her,

565
00:55:04,756 --> 00:55:08,324
<i>so I wouldn't have to imagine.</i>

566
00:55:08,360 --> 00:55:11,995
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

567
00:55:12,300 --> 00:55:14,300
(WHIMPERS)

568
00:55:23,641 --> 00:55:27,643
<i>CLAIRE: She was beautiful.</i>

569
00:55:27,679 --> 00:55:29,846
<i>So small.</i>

570
00:55:29,881 --> 00:55:34,884
I could cup her head in
the palm of my hand.

571
00:55:36,955 --> 00:55:41,457
The ears stuck out just a little.

572
00:55:41,493 --> 00:55:43,760
You could see the light through them.

573
00:55:43,795 --> 00:55:47,530
And the light through her skin as well.

574
00:55:47,565 --> 00:55:51,567
Like the light on a pearl

575
00:55:51,603 --> 00:55:55,838
that's still wet from the sea.

576
00:55:55,874 --> 00:55:58,808
Her eyes were closed.

577
00:56:01,613 --> 00:56:03,579
No lashes yet.

578
00:56:03,615 --> 00:56:06,349
They were slanted a bit,

579
00:56:06,384 --> 00:56:10,353
like yours.

580
00:56:10,388 --> 00:56:13,389
She had wisps of the most...

581
00:56:13,425 --> 00:56:15,958
beautiful copper hair.

582
00:56:15,994 --> 00:56:20,363
♪ Oh, I do like to be ♪

583
00:56:20,398 --> 00:56:23,800
<i>♪ Beside the seaside ♪</i>

584
00:56:23,835 --> 00:56:27,700
♪ Oh, I do like to be ♪

585
00:56:27,105 --> 00:56:30,600
♪ Beside the sea ♪

586
00:56:30,410 --> 00:56:33,476
♪ I like to walk along ♪

587
00:56:33,511 --> 00:56:36,479
♪ Prom, Prom, Prom ♪

588
00:56:36,514 --> 00:56:41,184
<i>♪ So just let me be beside the sea ♪</i>

589
00:56:48,626 --> 00:56:50,860
How long has it been?

590
00:56:51,750 --> 00:56:52,650
Since this morning.

591
00:57:30,340 --> 00:57:32,201
<i>Ma chère</i> Claire.

592
00:57:44,480 --> 00:57:48,500
She's beautiful, isn't she?

593
00:57:48,860 --> 00:57:50,153
<i>Oui.</i>

594
00:57:54,250 --> 00:57:56,759
Ten fingers.

595
00:57:56,794 --> 00:57:58,728
And ten toes.

596
00:58:02,700 --> 00:58:04,700
She's an angel.

597
00:58:13,440 --> 00:58:15,440
May I hold her?

598
00:58:25,557 --> 00:58:28,524
(SOMBER MUSIC)

599
00:58:28,560 --> 00:58:31,561
<i>♪ ♪</i>

600
00:58:44,542 --> 00:58:47,543
(SOBBING)

601
00:59:20,178 --> 00:59:23,179
(SOBBING)

602
00:59:48,206 --> 00:59:51,274
So yes...

603
00:59:55,460 --> 00:59:58,414
I hated you.

604
01:00:01,152 --> 01:00:03,152
Aye.

605
01:00:14,832 --> 01:00:16,832
But...

606
01:00:21,639 --> 01:00:23,806
it was me...

607
01:00:25,430 --> 01:00:27,337
who asked the impossible of you.

608
01:00:28,398 --> 01:00:32,566
It was me that put Frank
before our family.

609
01:00:32,821 --> 01:00:36,289
It was me...

610
01:00:36,645 --> 01:00:38,612
who followed you to the woods.

611
01:00:38,637 --> 01:00:40,970
Frank is your family too.

612
01:00:42,575 --> 01:00:44,575
But he's not here.

613
01:00:47,932 --> 01:00:50,333
And now, neither is our daughter.

614
01:00:54,559 --> 01:00:56,704
It's not your fault.

615
01:00:59,210 --> 01:01:02,548
It's not even Randall's
fault, not this time.

616
01:01:04,869 --> 01:01:06,369
It's my fault.

617
01:01:08,953 --> 01:01:10,386
(SIGHING)

618
01:01:10,429 --> 01:01:12,126
(SPEAKING GAELIC)

619
01:01:14,392 --> 01:01:17,572
I asked your forgiveness once.

620
01:01:18,486 --> 01:01:21,158
You said there's nothing to forgive.

621
01:01:22,925 --> 01:01:24,925
Truth is...

622
01:01:28,458 --> 01:01:30,868
I already forgave you,

623
01:01:32,529 --> 01:01:34,430
long before today.

624
01:01:35,588 --> 01:01:39,290
For this and anything
else you could ever do.

625
01:01:44,355 --> 01:01:46,856
There is something else.

626
01:01:51,798 --> 01:01:54,212
I slept with the king.

627
01:01:55,776 --> 01:01:57,556
To buy your freedom.

628
01:02:05,509 --> 01:02:07,813
You did it to save my life.

629
01:02:13,918 --> 01:02:17,189
Just like I gave myself
to Randall to save you.

630
01:02:32,437 --> 01:02:34,501
How can we ever be the same?

631
01:02:35,972 --> 01:02:37,790
No, we can't be.

632
01:02:40,876 --> 01:02:43,399
The weight of what has
happened here is...

633
01:02:44,816 --> 01:02:48,250
too much for any one
of us to bear alone.

634
01:02:55,260 --> 01:02:56,425
The only way we can live with it

635
01:02:56,461 --> 01:02:58,127
is to carry it...

636
01:03:00,965 --> 01:03:02,131
together.

637
01:03:04,402 --> 01:03:06,783
Are you sure you want to do that?

638
01:03:07,842 --> 01:03:09,517
We lost our child.

639
01:03:11,142 --> 01:03:15,411
But by the grace of God,
we may be given another.

640
01:03:19,920 --> 01:03:20,758
Then bring me home.

641
01:03:24,526 --> 01:03:25,691
To Scotland.

642
01:03:27,592 --> 01:03:28,757
Aye.

643
01:03:32,630 --> 01:03:33,229
Scotland.

644
01:03:34,499 --> 01:03:37,720
But there's something
I'd like to do first.

645
01:03:42,390 --> 01:03:45,400
<i>♪</i>

646
01:03:46,544 --> 01:03:48,544
St. Andrew.

647
01:04:02,894 --> 01:04:05,658
If we must bury you here in France,

648
01:04:07,498 --> 01:04:09,728
let's leave a bit of Scotland wi' ye.

649
01:04:10,658 --> 01:04:13,669
<i>♪</i>

650
